There are two ways for Apache webserver to access files from Glusterfs:

*1. Through Glusterfs mount pont:* The _DocumentRoot_ in Apache
configuration should refer to a directory on glusterfs mount point.

*2. Through Booster:* Booster is a library which can be LD_PRELOADed to
the application which wants to access files on glusterfs. Its a way
alternative to using FUSE for accessing glusterfs. Booster can be used
to save the overhead of context switches between user and kernel spaces
that happen with FUSE usage.

Among the above two methods, first one is straightforward and needs no
configuration other than mounting glusterfs on local filesystem. The
second method needs some configuration and is explained below.

Create simple server volume file.

For example, see the following /test/docs/server.vol file on the
GlusterFS server: volume localdisk type storage/posix option directory
/data/export end-volume volume localdisk-locked type features/locks
subvolumes localdisk end-volume volume localdisk-locked-iot type
performance/io-threads subvolumes localdisk-locked option thread-count 8
end-volume volume localdisk-server type protocol/server option
transport-type tcp option transport.socket.listen-port 2703 subvolumes
localdisk-locked-iot option auth.addr.localdisk-locked-iot.allow *
end-volume

Create a simple client volume file.

For example, see the following on /test/docs/client.vol on the system
running Apache.

`volume diskclient` +
`     type protocol/client` +
`     option transport-type tcp` +
`     option remote-port 2703` +
`     option remote-host brick1` +
`     option remote-subvolume locadisk-locked-iot` +
`end-volume` +
`volume disk-wb` +
`    type performance/write-behind` +
`    subvolumes diskclient` +
`end-volume`

Create a booster configuration file.

This configuration file establishes an association between a mount point
and the GlusterFS volume specification for accessing GlusterFS storage
bricks through this mount-point.

The following instructions show how to write a fstab file for booster.
(The booster configuration file has the same format as the Linux
/etc/fstab file.)

The booster.fstab file describes one volume per line.

For example, the following line tells booster to perform file system
operations that include /testpath/ as the root directory over the
GlusterFS volume called *localdiskthreads*:

`/docs/volfiles/localdiskiotclient.vol /testpath/ glusterfs subvolume=localdiskthreads,logfile=/test/clog,loglevel=DEBUG,attr_timeout=0`

The DocumentRoot of Apache should be on the virtual mount point
(/testpath/htdocs) or should be same same as the virtual mount point
(/testpath/).

For details on the comma-separated options in the last field of the
line, see BoosterConfiguration.

Define the required environment variables on the system running Apache.

The following using an environment variable tells booster about the
location of its booster.fstab file.

`$ export GLUSTERFS_BOOSTER_FSTAB=/etc/booster.fstab`

Start GlusterFS server on brick1:

`$ glusterfsd -f /test/docs/server.vol -L NONE -l /test/srvlog`

Start Apache.

(If you have changed the path to the glusterfs-booster.so library was
changed at installation, use the current path.)

`$ LD_PRELOAD=/usr/local/lib/glusterfs/glusterfs-booster.so httpd -f /usr/conf/httpd.conf`
